<div id="Idea_3006"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/3006-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_3006">potential for making mischief with crowd-sourcing (this site being an example)&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/4351-4049">ctb14</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">7 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">The government should be very careful with crowd-sourcing efforts. It is very easy for powerful interests to mobilize their members/friends to participate, skewing things in directions that are favorable to their views.  We already have examples of that on this site.  Imagine the AARP mobilizing its membership to re-write the laws for Social Security and Medicare.  In the real world, motivated and coached guidance from AARP to its membership would end up drowning out other voices.  That's why we have elected representatives, who have the choice to pay attention to highly-paid lobbyists, or not.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_3006" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_3006', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2242&topicID=3006')">Comments (3)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_3006"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2242">New Strategies and Techniques</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_3006"></div>
</div></td>
