<div id="Idea_2908"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/2908-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_2908">Random Citizen Congress&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/3974-4049">drwtwilner</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">8 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">One way to increase participation in the legislative process is to poll the citizenry prior to an actual vote in the House or Senate.  To make the poll relatively unbiased, begin by having a computer algorithm divide the Nation into districts of 30,000, as specified in the Constitution; then, before Congress votes on a bill, choose one person at random in each district, send them an email with a link to the bill's text, and record their yay-nay-abstain.  Make the results available to everyone: Congress, the media, the public.  Let's see if our Representatives agree with their constituents.</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_2908" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_2908', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2242&topicID=2908')">Comments (1)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_2908"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2242">New Strategies and Techniques</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=plebiscite">plebiscite</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_2908"></div>
</div></td>
